Rating: 4
These might be expensive but they really make a huge amount of squares. This will take you through the holiday season on your cookie plate, as they keep extremely well in the refrigerator, and they are so rich that they should be cut very small (3/4 inch square, in my opinion.) I baked the brownie layer for 20 minutes as written, and when I pulled them out of the oven they were still liquidy and bubbly-looking. I thought they were underdone but they were just right. I used Valrhona white and bittersweet chocolate for this, and it worked like a dream. I only had clear creme de menthe so I added a drop or two of green food coloring, but that's entirely optional. I believe they'd be just fine without it. I was hesitant to add the peppermint extract in addition to the creme de menthe for fear it would be too sharp and minty, but these proportions are just right. I'd urge others to use the creme de menthe, not just extract, as it gives a much deeper, more dimensional mint flavor without sharpness. I didn't cool the white chocolate ganache. I poured it warm over the cool brownie layer, and let it set up in the refrigerator. When it was firm I poured the bittersweet ganache, still warm. This method worked perfectly and saved a step. These are excellent and I will probably make them every Christmas. They can be made ahead of time, keep perfectly, and look great on the cookie plate. In short, they are a perfect Christmas cookie.

