Rating: 3
Made this for my annual cholesterol fest/holiday open house. They were very pretty, tasty, a nice little chocolate hit. I didn't "spread" the peppermint filling or ganache. I simply poured them while they were still somewhat liquid over the chilled layer below, then chilled it until it hardened. Very easy that way, and each layer was flat (except the brownie layer, which of course was a little wavy, but still pretty). I used peppermint schnapps instead of creme de menthe, because it's what I had. The flavor was very good, but I'd forgo the green food coloring I added when I make it next time -- white would have been fine. The peppermint layer was softer than the others, and I might try adding more white chocolate to it next time, and see if I like it better a bit firmer. As for cutting it into little squares, I would say that it's worth it to measure carefully, and definitely clean your knife thoroughly between cuts. This results in the cleanest, prettiest squares, and is worth the trouble.

Rating: 4
My daughter made this for my cookie exchange. (ok, I did most of the work) They were the favorite cookie of the party. After reading the directions first, I decided we would cut a few corners. (it was 2 am the night before the party) So I didn't let the ganache thicken before putting over the brownies. I put the brownie in the fridge to set up quickly, then put the mint ganache on top. I returned it to the fridge and then 1/2 hour later did the same with the chocolate ganache. They were a little messy at first, but ended up being wonderful!! When I make these again, I will do it the same way.

